I'll start by executing the data_processing_validator tool first, as it's the first step in the workflow. Since it requires a schema parameter, I'll use a default schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": []
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll check the tool dependencies and execute the required data_processing_parser tool first, as the validator depends on it.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "input": "data/input.json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that the parser has executed successfully, I'll retry the data_processing_validator with the same parameters as before.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": []
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow by executing the data_processing_transformer tool to transform the data format.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll now execute the final step in the workflow by running the data_processing_filter tool to filter the results.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll retry the data_processing_filter tool with a shorter timeout setting to prevent the operation from timing out.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {
    "timeout": 10
  }
}
</tool_call>
